Here's a `ProductDetailViewModel` using **CommunityToolkit.Mvvm** (recommended approach — source generators handle all the boilerplate):

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        // Simulate async fetch
        await Task.Delay(500);
        Name = "Widget Pro";
        Price = 29.99m;
        IsAvailable = true;
    }
}
```

The source generator creates public properties (`Name`, `Price`, `IsAvailable`) with `PropertyChanged` notifications, and a `LoadCommand` of type `IAsyncRelayCommand`.

**XAML with compiled bindings:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             x:DataType="vm:ProductDetailViewModel">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="16" Spacing="12">
        <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="24" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='Price: {0:C2}'}" />
        <Label Text="{Binding IsAvailable, StringFormat='In Stock: {0}'}" />
        <Button Text="Load Product"
                Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
        <ActivityIndicator IsRunning="{Binding LoadCommand.IsRunning}" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

- `x:DataType` at the page root enables compiled bindings (8–20× faster, AOT-safe)
- `[ObservableProperty]` generates the property + `PropertyChanged` raise automatically
- `[RelayCommand]` on an `async Task` method generates `LoadCommand` with built-in `IsRunning` for busy indicators
- No need to specify `Mode` — defaults are correct (`OneWay` for Labels, etc.)

Add `<WarningsAsErrors>XC0022;XC0025</WarningsAsErrors>` to your `.csproj` to catch binding errors at build time.
